x4freetext: The targets thickness were
1.5 microg/cm2.
The elastic data were taken at 160, 135, 105 and 90
degrees, while the inelastic data were taken at 160,
135 and 105 or 90 degrees. The measurements for
elastic and inelastic scattering were made
simultaneously. Near-resonance data were taken in
energy steps of 100 eV, while off-resonance data were
measured in energy steps <=400 eV. The resolution was
maintained at 250-350 eV (FWHM of Gaussian resolution
function) throughout. Most of the more complex
regions were taken with resolution <= 300 eV.
Improved detector collimation reduced the background
in the vicinity of the inelastic peak as compared
with our earlier experiments. The improved inelastic
data were critical in determining the spin of many of
the resonances.

x4freetext: All of the data were analysed using a
multi-level, multi-channel R-matrix computer. The
following resonance parameters were varied: spin J,
parity pi, resonance energy, elastic and inelastic
scattering widths. Spin assignments were based on
shape analysis of the elastic resonances and upon the
inelastic angular distributions.
Hard-sphere phase shifts to L=4.

uncertainties. The errors in the elastic widths range
from 10% for very strong  resonances to as much as
50 % for  very weak  resonances. The larger inelastic
widths should be accurate to 25% or better.
